00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.720
If a company is mining something,
there are usually byproducts,

00:00:02.720 --> 00:00:05.280
the stuff that's left behind after
extraction and processing.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:08.240
And these days, the mining company should
be required to deal with those byproducts,

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:10.720
but in the past they often
just piled them up

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:12.640
and assumed someone would deal
with the problem

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:14.080
at some point in the future.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:16.640
If those byproducts are toxic,
that’s a problem.

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:19.600
But here in Hirschau, in Germany,
it's a bit different.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:22.000
Just over there is an
open-pit kaolin mine:

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.280
kaolin is a really common mineral

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:24.960
that's used in the manufacture
of a lot of things,

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.200
everything from pottery to toothpaste.

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:30.240
And there is a big pile of
mining byproduct here.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:33.040
I'm standing on it,
it is 120 metres high.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:36.000
But it's just sand.
Regular sand. Made of quartz,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.440
like what you'd find in the desert.

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:39.280
Quartz sand can be useful in industry.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.680
These days the sand that the mines
produce here is sold off.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:44.000
But for decades there was
too much of it,

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.680
so as it was pretty harmless,
the mining companies just piled it up.

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.880
What do you do with 35 million tons of sand,
in a pile that's dominating the landscape?

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:56.080
The answer, of course, is
make it a tourist attraction.

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:00.000
Welcome to the ski resort and
amusement park of Mount Kaolino.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.640
I should point out — it’s 9am on
a weekday as I’m filming this,

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:04.720
so there aren’t many people around,
it's not fully open.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:06.320
In the summer school holidays,

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:09.680
this place is as busy as a
regular ski slope would be in high season.

